Introduction to ape library¶

1. Read our first tree in Newick format¶

In [3]:
%%R --type=cairo
simpletree <- ape::read.tree(text = "(((A,B), (C,D)), E);")
simpletree

Phylogenetic tree with 5 tips and 4 internal nodes.

Tip labels:
  A, B, C, D, E

Rooted; no branch lengths.

2. Plot our tree¶

In [4]:
%%R --type=cairo
ape::plot.phylo(simpletree)

Plot the same three but as unrooted:

In [5]:
%%R --type=cairo
ape::plot.phylo(simpletree, type="unrooted")

3. Save our picture¶

Saving in png

In [6]:
%%R --type=cairo
png("results/simpletree.png") # open device for plotting
ape::plot.phylo(simpletree) # plotting
dev.off() # close our device and save file

png 
  2

Saving in svg

In [7]:
%%R --type=cairo
png("results/simpletree.svg")
ape::plot.phylo(simpletree)
dev.off()

png 
  2

4. Load tree¶

In [8]:
%%R --type=cairo
tree_of_life <- ape::read.tree("https://www.jasondavies.com/tree-of-life/life.txt")
tree_of_life

Phylogenetic tree with 191 tips and 190 internal nodes.

Tip labels:
  Escherichia_coli_EDL933, Escherichia_coli_O157_H7, Escherichia_coli_O6, Escherichia_coli_K12, Shigella_flexneri_2a_2457T, Shigella_flexneri_2a_301, ...
Node labels:
  , Bacteria, 66, 74, 98, 82, ...

Rooted; includes branch lengths.

5. Tree plotting¶

In [9]:
%%R --type=cairo
ape::plot.phylo(tree_of_life)

We can plot the same tree using function from standard package

In [10]:
%%R --type=cairo
plot(tree_of_life)

Let’s prettify our plot (by text size reduction: parameter cex)

In [11]:
%%R --type=cairo
ape::plot.phylo(tree_of_life, cex = 0.2)

Save results:

In [12]:
%%R --type=cairo
png(filename = "results/treeOfLife.png", width = 20, height = 20, units = "cm", res = 600)
ape::plot.phylo(tree_of_life, cex = 0.2)
dev.off()

png 
  2

6. Plotting tree as unrooted and radial¶

Plot the same tree but make it unrooted

In [13]:
%%R --type=cairo
plot.phylo(tree_of_life, type = "unrooted", no.margin = T, cex=0.5)

Plot tree in radial format

In [14]:
%%R --type=cairo
ape::plot.phylo(tree_of_life, type = "radial", cex=0.2)

Introduction to ggtree library¶

7. Plot our tree using ggtree with minimal settings¶

There is no information about taxa names

In [15]:
%%R --type=cairo
ggtree(tree_of_life)

8. Display information about taxa names¶

In [16]:
%%R --type=cairo
ggtree(tree_of_life) + geom_tiplab(size = 1)

9. Plot circular tree¶

In [17]:
%%R --type=cairo
ggtree(tree_of_life) + layout_circular() + geom_tiplab(size = 2)

R[write to console]: Scale for 'y' is already present. Adding another scale for 'y', which will
replace the existing scale.

Be careful! The order of commands is important for correct visualization. If we break it, we can obtain wrong results

In [18]:
%%R --type=cairo
ggtree(tree_of_life) + geom_tiplab(size = 2) + layout_circular()

R[write to console]: Scale for 'y' is already present. Adding another scale for 'y', which will
replace the existing scale.

10. Highlight some group on the picture¶

In [21]:
%%R --type=cairo
tree_of_life <- groupOTU(tree_of_life, c("Homo_sapiens", "Pan_troglodytes"))
ggtree(tree_of_life) + layout_circular() +
geom_tiplab2(size = 2) + geom_tippoint(aes(alpha = group), col = "red") +
scale_color_manual(values = c(0,1), aesthetics = "alpha") +
theme(legend.position = 'null')

R[write to console]: Scale for 'y' is already present. Adding another scale for 'y', which will
replace the existing scale.
In [22]:
%%R --type=cairo
ggtree(tree_of_life) + layout_circular() + geom_tiplab(size = 2) +
geom_text2(aes(subset=!isTip, label=node), size = 3, col = "red")

R[write to console]: Scale for 'y' is already present. Adding another scale for 'y', which will
replace the existing scale.

Color some part of the tree by its node

In [23]:
%%R --type=cairo
ggtree(tree_of_life) + layout_circular() + geom_tiplab2(size = 2) +
geom_hilight(node = 219, fill = "gold") +
geom_cladelabel(node = 219, label = "Here", fontsize = 2, offset = 1)

R[write to console]: Scale for 'y' is already present. Adding another scale for 'y', which will
replace the existing scale.

13. Plotting tree as a picture¶

Plot out tree as a picture and save it.

Parameter: do_show=False allows to save this picture into the file (otherwise it will be empty)

In [29]:
Phylo.draw(tree1, do_show=False);
plt.savefig("results/py_tree1_phylo.svg")
plt.savefig("results/py_tree1_phylo.png")

Biopython advantage: we can convert phylogenic tree from one format to another

In [30]:
tree1 = tree1.as_phyloxml()
Phylo.write(tree1, "results/tree1.xml", "phyloxml")
Out[30]:
1

14. Picture tunning to make it more readable¶

In [31]:
tree1.clade[0, 1].color = "blue"
plt.rc('font', size=1)
plt.figure(figsize=(24,12))
Phylo.draw(tree1, do_show = False)
plt.savefig("results/py_tree1_phylo_blue.png", dpi=600)

<Figure size 1728x864 with 0 Axes>

ETE (ETE3)¶

15. Load our tree¶

In [32]:
raw_tree = requests.get('https://www.jasondavies.com/tree-of-life/life.txt').text

Convert loaded data into the tree object

In [33]:
tree2 = Tree(raw_tree, format=1)
tree2
Out[33]:
Tree node '' (0x7f94cb46a3d)

16. Plotting tree as a picture¶

In [34]:
tree2.render("results/py_tree2_ete3.pdf");

TreeStyle allows to draw some interesting graphs

In [35]:
circular_style = TreeStyle()
circular_style.mode = "c"
circular_style.scale = 20
tree2.render("results/py_tree2_ete3_circ.pdf", tree_style=circular_style);

17. Tree prunning¶

Prune some piece of the tree for better visualization and interpretation.

Here we sample random 42 leaves from the tree

In [36]:
ss = random.sample(tree2.get_leaf_names(), 42)
tree2.prune(ss)
tree2.render("results/py_tree2_ete3_random.pdf");
